      {
        "urn": "urn:li:activity:7446977528835170304",
        "url": "https://www.linkedin.com/posts/markjacobstein_as-ive-written-about-before-i-think-we-activity-7446977528835170304-08ef?utm_source=social_share_send&utm_medium=member_desktop_web&rcm=ACoAAGbYilkBsT-7xuT6Ux9P0MMOzZMgTeRaYDw",
        "post_type": "repost",
        "posted_at": "2026-04-06 20:52:39",
        "timestamp_ms": 1775501559882,
        "text": "As I’ve written about before, I think we’re hitting the “meringue moment” in techbio; after years (decades?) of excitement regarding computable biology, the future is here (if unevenly distributed).\n\nLast Monday, I convened a group of the world’s frontier techbio builders at Stanford to discuss their projects and expand each other’s horizons. We had South Park Commons funded founders (Helena de Puig, Erkin Kuru, Michaël Moret, Robin Guo, Kam Leong, Evgeny Kiner, Danny Wells), members (Niokhor Dione, Suraj Pavagada, Stanford Professors (Aaron Newman, Ansuman Satpathy, and Natalia Gomez-Ospina), and old colleagues from industry (Andrew Pannu, Alexandria Cogdill).\n\nIt was a fantastic session (though ~10 PhDs still couldn’t solve all our Zoom challenges), and, as always, the fact that everyone was working on distinct challenges was a feature, not a bug. If this sounds interesting to you, and your work is on the edge of computational biology, apply to SPC!",
        "author": {
          "name": "Mark Jacobstein",
          "username": null,
          "url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/markjacobstein?miniProfileUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afsd_profile%3AACoAAAAB0DYBaoshjpdcCY10ekUDtZ97WzyeU0E"
